pd_0_com_1text: Ah, the detective. Mr. ShAIRlock Holmes.
pd_0_com_2text: Have you already figured anything out?
pd_0_com_3text: That reminds me of a story from the war, a case of the military police...
pd_1_com_0text: I can't imagine this being relevant to the case.
pd_2_com_0text: Yes, young people like you cannot even imagine the war.
pd_2_com_1text: We had fought the airplanes back then.
pd_2_com_2text: Balloon against plane. Those were the days.
pd_2_com_3text: Days when there was still heroism and real camaraderie.
pd_2_com_4text: I fought side by side with Lord Zeppelin back then.
pd_3_com_0text: [The general and the lord know each other from the war?]
pd_4_com_0text: I tell you, the planes are all the same. They have no honor.
pd_4_com_1text: Believe me, I've seen things no balloon should see.
pd_4_com_2text: Comrades, good friends who popped right and left of me as we were being shot at by darts.
pd_4_com_3text: Melted balloon rubber scorched by flames. I'll never forget that smell.
pd_4_com_4text: The enemies even used their feared glass splinter gas when we had to entrench ourselves against their attacks.
pd_4_com_5text: That's not something you can imagine.
pd_4_com_6text: Nevertheless, we managed to strike back the enemies and protect our homeland.
pd_4_com_7text: Maybe the planes got the lord after all these years?
pd_5_com_0text: I believe that foreign involvement is extremely unlikely in this case.
pd_6_com_0text: Yeah, I also believe the planes can never get to us, balloons.
pd_6_com_1text: Balloons will always rule. Rule, Balloonia!
pd_8_com_2text: Balloons never, never, never shall be slaves.
pd_10_com_2text: May I ask you a few questions?
pd_12_com_0text: [What should I ask the general about?]
pd_17_com_0text: Oh, I see how it goes.
pd_17_com_1text: You want to confuse an old man like me with your questions.
pd_17_com_2text: You are a cunning fox, Mr Holmes.
pd_17_com_3text: But I'm sure I can't tell you anything about you that you don't already know or have been printed in all the newspapers in this city.
pd_17_com_4text: But if instead you want to hear a story about my wartime experiences...
pd_18_com_0text: I'm very appreciative of your offer, but that won't be necessary.
pd_19_com_0text: Oh, yes, the lady hot-air balloon. A young and pretty balloon.
pd_19_com_1text: Why did she marry the older Lord Zeppelin? Isn't that obvious? For the same reason all young girls marry older balloons like us. All she cares about is money.
pd_19_com_2text: And with the death of the Lord Zeppelin, she is now also heir to his not inconsiderable wealth.
pd_19_com_3text: I wouldn't be surprised if in a few months she remarried to a young, handsome, energetic man.
pd_20_com_0text: She is the sole heiress of Lord Zeppelin's great wealth?
pd_20_com_1text: [That sounds like a possible motive for murdering her husband.]
pd_21_com_0text: For example, the young chef. I have seen how they look at each other.
pd_21_com_1text: I live long enough to know there's definitely something going on between them.
pd_22_com_0text: Thank you very much for this conversation, General.
pd_22_com_1text: I'll ask the lady and the chef about it.
pd_22_com_2text: [If the lady and the cook are secretly a couple, both would have had a reason to get rid of Lord Zeppelin.]
pd_23_com_0text: Please don't mention I told you that.
pd_24_com_1text: I don't have any more questions.
pd_26_com_0text: Please just answer the question truthfully.
pd_27_com_0text: All right! All right! I'll tell you about it.
pd_27_com_1text: It may be that my company hasn't been doing quite as well lately as it used to.
pd_29_com_0text: My company hasn't been doing quite as well lately as it used to.
pd_29_com_1text: I had to cut the budget in the company and lay off some employees.
pd_29_com_2text: But to make the company competitive again, I would have to invest in new machines, but I don't have the money for that.
pd_29_com_3text: That's why I'm here today. I had talked to the Lord Zeppelin and he promised me financial help.
pd_30_com_0text: So the sudden death of Lord Zeppelin is very inconvenient for you.
pd_30_com_1text: [I don't think the lord would be willing to lend so much money just like that.]
pd_31_com_0text: How can you say such a thing? He is one of my oldest friends!
pd_31_com_1text: But yes, now I unfortunately have to find another supporter if I don't want to go broke.
pd_31_com_2text: What a pity in my old days.
pd_31_com_4text: It is the "Venerable cross of the brave sword balloons".
pd_31_com_5text: Only Knights of the Royal Balloon Order receive the honor of wearing such a medal.
pd_31_com_6text: This medal was awarded to me by the King himself.
pd_31_com_7text: Those were the honorable days. And now I'm supposed to go from house to house begging for money like a bum?
pd_31_com_8text: How did it get so far that our society treats its veteran heroes like this?
pd_32_com_0text: [The general seems to be a very proud man. But how far is he willing to go to protect his honor?]
pd_32_com_1text: I wouldn't worry you'd ever end up homeless on the street. Even if your business goes bankrupt, generals out of service get a state pension.
pd_33_com_0text: Mr. ShAIRlock Holmes, you are a naive young balloon.
pd_34_com_0text: The cook? He is like all Airlander: lazy, unpunctual, hectic, impulsive, a womanizer who doesn't know anything about our reliable Ballonian cuisine.
pd_35_com_0text: Have you ever spoken to him?
pd_36_com_0text: No and I don't have to, I know balloons like him: The Airlanders!
pd_36_com_1text: *I think he's a member of the Mafia that does the drugs.*
pd_37_com_0text: [I do not consider this information to be particularly reliable.]
pd_38_com_0text: I'll tell you that based on my life experience, Mr. Holmes.
pd_38_com_1text: As you get older, you'll understand.
pd_39_com_0text: Are you suggesting that Lord Zeppelin had the cook work for him without a work permit or taxation?
pd_40_com_0text: How can you say such an outrageous thing, Mr. Holmes?
pd_40_com_1text: Beware of the Airlander, Mr. Holmes, he is dangerous and takes advantage of you by inciting you against your own countrymen.
pd_42_com_0text: I knew you'd come to hear my story.
pd_42_com_1text: But who can blame you? After all, it's a story of epic proportion.
pd_42_com_2text: What should I tell you first?
pd_42_com_3text: The story of how I alone stopped the invasion of planes across the Balloon Channel for 40 hours until the reinforcements finally arrived?
pd_43_com_0text: [I remember reading about it. But it was a whole squadron and only 10 hours. Still an impressive achievement.]
pd_44_com_0text: Or how I caught several dart grenades out of midair with my bare hands and threw them back to the enemies?
pd_46_com_0text: Or how I spent 24 hours alone behind enemy lines for a bet?
pd_48_com_0text: Or how the King himself thanked me for my service to Balloonia.
pd_49_com_0text: [Since the General wears the "Venerable cross of the brave sword balloons", this must be true.]
pd_49_com_1text: Thank you for your time, General. I think I was able to get a clear impression of you.
pd_50_com_0text: But I haven't even started telling the story yet...
pd_51_com_0text: If there is nothing more, you are dismissed.
